## Diagnosis

The `micro` mode was introduced as a responsive typographic tier for very small tiles (32–64px wide), rendering category names at ~8px. This is below the WCAG minimum legible threshold and produces text that is functionally unreadable — it only *looks* like a label.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Progressive Disclosure Suppressed Instead of Applied.**

The anti-pattern: when a container is too small to display content legibly, the wrong response is to *shrink the font until it fits*. The correct response is to *hide the text entirely and surface it through another mechanism* (tooltip, hover state, aria-label). Micro-font rendering gives the visual impression of a label while providing zero actual information — worse than showing nothing, because it creates false affordance.

---

## Fix

### 1. Remove the `micro` typography tier from the tile renderer

**`components/knowledge-treemap/KnowledgeTreemapTile.tsx`**

```tsx
// BEFORE — three tiers including the broken micro tier
type DisplayMode = 'full' | 'compact' | 'micro'

function getDisplayMode(width: number, height: number): DisplayMode {
  if (width < 64 || height < 32) return 'micro'   // ← remove this tier
  if (width < 120 || height < 60) return 'compact'
  return 'full'
}

// Inside the render:
{mode === 'micro' && (
  <span className="text-[8px] leading-none truncate">{category.name}</span>
)}
{mode === 'compact' && (
  <span className="text-xs leading-tight truncate">{category.name}</span>
)}
{mode === 'full' && (
  <span className="text-sm leading-snug">{category.name}</span>
)}
```

```tsx
// AFTER — two tiers only; micro tiles get no visible text, only accessible markup
type DisplayMode = 'full' | 'compact' | 'hidden'

function getDisplayMode(width: number, height: number): DisplayMode {
  if (width < 64 || height < 32) return 'hidden'
  if (width < 120 || height < 60) return 'compact'
  return 'full'
}

export function KnowledgeTreemapTile({ category, width, height, ...props }) {
  const mode = getDisplayMode(width, height)

  return (
    <div
      // Always present for screen readers regardless of visual mode
      title={category.name}          // native browser tooltip on hover
      aria-label={category.name}
      role="img"
      {...props}
    >
      {mode === 'compact' && (
        <span
          className="text-xs leading-tight truncate block px-1"
          aria-hidden="true"         // aria-label on parent already covers it
        >
          {category.name}
        </span>
      )}

      {mode === 'full' && (
        <span
          className="text-sm leading-snug block px-2 py-1"
          aria-hidden="true"
        >
          {category.name}
        </span>
      )}

      {/* mode === 'hidden': no visible text; title + aria-label carry semantics */}
    </div>
  )
}
```

### 2. Add a tooltip for hidden-mode tiles

If you have a Tooltip primitive in Elan, wrap the tile:

**`components/knowledge-treemap/KnowledgeTreemap.tsx`**

```tsx
// In the tile rendering loop:
{tiles.map((tile) => {
  const mode = getDisplayMode(tile.width, tile.height)

  const tileEl = (
    <KnowledgeTreemapTile
      key={tile.id}
      category={tile.category}
      width={tile.width}
      height={tile.height}
      style={{ ...tile.style }}
    />
  )

  // Wrap tiny tiles in a Tooltip so the name is still discoverable
  return mode === 'hidden' ? (
    <Tooltip key={tile.id} content={tile.category.name} side="top">
      {tileEl}
    </Tooltip>
  ) : tileEl
})}
```

### 3. Purge the Tailwind class so it can't drift back in

Add to your Tailwind config safelist's *blocklist* (Tailwind 4 uses `blocklist` in `@theme`):

**`app/globals.css` (or your `@theme` file)**

```css
@theme {
  /* … existing tokens … */

  /* Prevent sub-legible font sizes from entering the design system */
  --text-micro: initial;   /* unset any micro token if it exists */
}
```

Or in `tailwind.config.ts` if you're still bridging v3 config:

```ts
// tailwind.config.ts
export default {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      fontSize: {
        // Do NOT add 'micro' here. Ever.
        // Minimum legible size is 'xs' (12px / 0.75rem).
      }
    }
  }
}
```

---

## Principle

**Never scale text below legibility; hide it instead.**

The threshold is **12px / 0.75rem** (WCAG 1.4.4, browser minimum font-size floor). When a container cannot accommodate that minimum at any font-weight:

1. **Remove the visible text** — do not shrink it.
2. **Preserve the semantic label** via `aria-label`, `title`, or a tooltip component.
3. **Treat the tile as a glyph**, not a label — colour, position, and tooltip carry the identity.

The rule to enforce in code review: *if a font-size value is expressed in `px` and is less than 12, or is `text-[anything-below-xs]`, it is a bug, not a design choice.* Any responsive typography tier below `text-xs` should be replaced by a visibility decision (`hidden` / tooltip), never a size decision.
